title: Modular Snap-Fit Airship
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text: This is a fully modular snap-fit (no glue required) model of an Airship. It is the vanilla base for a series of absurd mashups that currently includes a Trireme and a Saturn V rocket. Designed for 3D print, it comes in two flavors: solid and shell.

Both the shell and solid versions have been prototyped on a Replicator 2 with no supports (and no raft but that depends on your confidence with over/under-sticking). Sliced in skeinforge it works best at I had good results with the following settings in print-o-matic: no support/no raft
layer thickness: .15mm (or less)
Number of shells: 1 or 2
feed speed: 80mm/s
travel speed: 150mm/s
fill rate: 0 (for shell version) or .1 (for solid version) My actual slice profile is a little more complex but with print-o-matic those are the settings that will get you started. The shell version was designed to keep the material use to a minimum and works quite well but I think the solid might actually print faster at low rates of infill because there is less shell and perimeter to print even though they have been minimized in the shell version. The snap fit is pretty self-explanitory with the seperate H-clips intended to attach the two main halves together with the nose and tail cones snapping into the integrated snap prong features on the main body. The propellers just push into place. Print two and you can have a four engine Mega-Airship and a windowless drone ship! Or check out the Trireme and Saturn V upgrades to make a mega crazy super cool ultra futuristic ancient star ship. Coming soon: Riverboat and a Warp Nacell upgrades! Trireme Hull: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:45305
Saturn V: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:45316 This is a work in progress for an art series I am working on so for the moment I licensed it as no-derivatives but I will open it up soon after I finish a few more parts.

title: Prusa LM8UU Carriage for Qu-BD extruders

description.text: Based off of julienM's work. Simply kludged space for an LM8UU bearing. In the process I had to widen the rod slots as well to ensure no contact/friction along the model. Note: julienM also created an LM8UU version of this at the same time. You should test that one as well. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:41986 The bearing holes and the rod shafts are purposely a little large to allow for a tiny bit of displacement to match your specific rod width. Use zip ties to ensure the bearings stay in place. Update: Added an instruction for drilling the mounting plate holes, as per JulienM's suggestion.

• Print (should be in ABS due to the heat in the area).
  • Drill holes for the zip ties, and clean up any frayed threads inside the bearing holes. (sorry - I was too anxious to get the thing printed and didn't put holes for the zip ties into the model.)
  • Mount your bearings and zip ties, but do not tighten the zip ties yet. If the print cracks a little along the outer edge, don't worry too much about this as the zip ties will then hold things in place. If you are concerned, a little ABS glue will work well.
  • Mount your QU-BD extruder plate. Drill holes for the mounting screws where needed, and bolt the plate in place (with the extruder attached).
  • Mount the carriage to your Prusa.
  • Tighten down the zip ties.
  • Enjoy your printer.

title: Lemon RX PPM Receiver w/ Failsafe Enclosure

description.text: I recently bought an Lemon RX DSMX PPM 8-channel Receiver + Satellite and Failsafe (http://www.lemon-rx.com/shop/index.php?route=product/product&product_id=118). The receiver board comes sans enclosure (strange, since the satellite comes with an enclosure) so I built my own. This is the first version and hasn't flown yet. Its rather thin-walled to keep weight down and I suspect I'll increase the wall thickness by 2-3 fold to improve the protection it provides to the board inside. The top is a loose friction fit - my expectation is to use zip-ties to both keep the top closed during flight and hold the box to the vehicle. There is a small ledge on the inside which the board sits on and a small column protruding from the top that keeps the board from jostling around. I've cut holes in the side to allow for the antenna, the failsafe button, the headers and the JST plug to be accessible through the walls of the enclosure. I will probably refine those in the future. Upon request, added a new slot to accommodate a new version of the receiver that includes a diversity antenna. I don't have one so I've guessed at the required position based on another user's feedback - thank you @Hfamilyfun for the comments.

This was printed on a Makerbot Replicator 2 using Matterhacker's Black 1.75mm filamant without a raft, directly on the acrylic build plate - no painter's tape.  It was printed at standard quality (200micron layer thickness) and 120mm/s speed at 205 degrees C.

description.text:
This is a highly detailed snap-fit (no glue required) model of a Saturn V rocket. Its modular design and included conversion ring makes it fully compatible with my Modular Snap-Fit Airship and Trireme Upgrade:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:45295
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:45305 Uploaded an optimized version on 1/21/2013. Version 3 has improved wall thicknesses on the shells for two loop printing on almost every layer. The resulting build is more sturdy and efficent. The individual pieces are now avilable as well.

The Modular Snap-Fit Saturn V has been prototyped on a Replicator 2. It is designed for support free printing and has been prototyped as such. UPDATE: 1/31/2013
Version 3 is now online and it includes some improvements and optimizations. If you are a Replicator or Replicator2 user try slicing in MakerWare's Slice engine with .15mm layers and zero infill (not skeinforge). The latest prototype was sliced in this way and it took less than five minutes and the quality is comporable to a much slower Skinforge slice! I will post a more detailed MakerWare slice profile later. Sliced in skeinforge it works best with the following settings in print-o-matic: no support/raft
layer thickness: .15mm (or less)
Number of shells: 2 or 3 (This setting is very important to make the vertical prongs on the two middle sections strong enough to survive repeated snap-fitting)
feed speed: 80mm/s
travel speed: 150mm/s
fill rate: 0 (for shell version) My actual slice profile is a little more complex but with print-o-matic those are the settings that will get you started. WARNING! Due to the high detail of the original solid model (B-rep made in autodesk Inventor) the resulting .stl surface mesh is very complex. Slicing can take a while even on high-spec machines. This shell version was designed to keep the material use to a minimum and works quite well but I am working on a solid version anyway. It might actually print faster at low rates of infill because there is less shell and perimeter to print even though they have been minimized in the shell version. If you Saturn V comes out a little loose on the top and tail (like my last one did) I uploaded a quick fix so you can print a pair of shims that should tighten it up. They almost must be printed at .15 layers with the bottom layer at 100% thickness to work. This model also replaces the tail and nose or hull sections of my Modular Snap-Fit Airship converting it into an Saturn V Airship! The included adaptder ring makes for a smooth transition between the airship and the S-IVb (top) section of the Saturn V. The same is true for the Trireme Hull! Airship: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:45295
Trireme: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:45305 This is a work in progress for an art series I am working on so for the moment I licensed it as no-derivatives but I will open it up soon after I finish a few more parts.

This is my first attempt at ROM Spaceknight. Made in Tinkercad, the design was based on original drawings by Sal Buscema. The model started as just a bust, but ultimately deserved arms and legs. A lot of the construction is influenced by the original Parker Brothers toy.

In issue #2 the narrator states that ROM has "red eyes blazing like live coals!" To recreate this effect, I've left the eye holes hollow and made the back of the head wall thin enough to let light in. This model has a slot on the top of the head to insert a small piece of red lighting gel. When light passes through, it should give the appearance of glowing red eyes (untested).

I do realize ROM is a cyborg, but there is only a Model Robots category.

Gain 11 milllimeters of your Z travel back! This printable mod lets you alter your Makerbot Automated Build Platform to shrink it vertically by 11 millimeters by moving the motor to the rear. The parts are also laser cuttable. Benefits:
  • Get more height out of your Makerbot builds
  • Uses hardware bundled with the Automated Build Platform - no trips to the hardware store
  • Lighter weight and shorter height improve platform movement performance
    • Known issues:
  • The piece that holds the nozzle cleaner will probably not print correctly unless you\'re blowing on it while it\'s printing.
  • The nozzle cleaner prints on both front pieces but must be cut off on the inner one (because it interferes with the belt).
  • The gears hit the side of the Makerbot\'s window at x <= -45 and y >= 40.
  • At high heat levels the printed parts may melt or deform. Shouldn\'t be a big issue since the hot part is still wood contact only.
  • Due to printing tolerances, the surface may not be perfectly level and may need to be shimmed.
    • Note that in the images I have the wood base for the heating PCB flipped around 180 degrees. I had to do this because I had incorrectly positioned it in Blender. The STL files and Blender source are all corrected now though, and you will not have to turn that piece of wood around.

Make sure to set your Skeinforge to print with a few extra shells to increase the strength of the parts. Print two of the front piece, two of the rear piece, and one of the chute piece.  Cut one of the brush holder protrusions off of one of the front pieces.  Use them to replace the sides and front of your Automated Build Platform assembly. 
Also, you will need to reverse the terminals on the belt motor because it needs to turn the opposite way when located on the rear.

title: Specialized 05FSR > Blackburn Dirt Merchant Rear Fender Adapter

description.text:
my dirt merchant rear fender recently died and broke off... perhaps it was tired of living as it promptly scuttled under a nearby car and took me a bit of time to retrieve!  anyhow i decided to disappoint it by creating this mount and dragging it, kicking and screaming, back into service.  (you will have to die another day, dirt merchant!)
This is an adapter to mount a particular kind of rear fender (a blackburn dirt merchant) to the swingarm of a particular mountain bike (a specialized 05fsr xc comp).  as you will notice from the pics, i have some incredibly small 1.25" road tires mounted on my 21" rims, so with the mount, the fender will not clear normal knobby MTB tires.
chances are, few of you will happen to have this combination of bike / fender / tires lying around, but perhaps this part will serve as a decent basis for your own design - it probably would not take much work to adapt it to another dual suspension bike, or perhaps add parts to be able to print a full rear fender?
in the pics i left the part in orange for clarity, although i will probably spray it black.

for my bike, uniform scaling so that the y-axis is 138mm long works well.  (not needing something very pretty) i just stuck with the standard medium settings on my rep 2, v7 firmware.
the part screws into the fender with two screws, snaps onto two legs of the swingarm, and then zip-ties in front with one zip-tie.

description.text: I had trouble printing phineasjw's Replicator Bed Level Jig (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:23257) with ABS. Indicator was going in fine with enough pressure, but holes for magnets were almost 1mm smaller so created an OpenSCAD file to allow for making bigger holes. Download both the .scad file from here and a V2 STL from the original Thing. Then just adjust magnet size (hole_diameter) and account for material tolerance (hole_tolerance). Both will be added up and you just need to export STL from OpenSCAD.

This is a mod for the SeeMeCNC ezstruder, allowing it to use a MK8 hobbed gear and bowden passthrough connector. You'll need an ezstruder, as it uses the bearing arm that comes with it. Technically you could source the bearing and spring yourself, but it helps to start with the original. You'll also need an E3D (or Prometheus) passthrough connector for the bowden tube, and a MK8 hobbed gear.
The end result is the MK8 provides ~34% more torque than the original MK7 gear, and the passthrough means that the bowden tube runs right up to the gear, helping keep the filament snag free. EDIT After lots of testing, here are the existing issues: The faceplate which helps keep the red arm aligned can loosen over time, I need to embed a nut for to hold the screw instead of just threading into plastic. Also, the spring pressure is a liiittle strong, with one spool of ABS the filament would sometimes get flattened.

I didn't mark down which screws need replacing, but you'll find that some of the original screws for the ezstruder will now be a touch too short.
The cylinder that replaces the aluminum one in the original has BSP threads for the passthrough connector, so it may be helpful to print it on a resin printer if you have access to one, but it'll probably still work on a regular FDM printer.
All of the parts are 1-1 replacements, so just print them out and assemble exactly as they were in the original. Also, you'll notice that the passthrough connector will prevent the bowden tube from going down, but to stop it from creeping up into the hobbed gear, wrap some kapton (or other strong tape) around the tube as shown in the picture to keep it locked solidly in place.
All of the parts should be printed with very high infill, preferably out of PLA as it's stiffer than ABS. The faceplate helps keep the bearing arm aligned, so that should be printed solid.

title: VEND - the totally printed candy dispenser

description.text: My new YouTube Channel: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCnnw56J_TeOsF4M_F5pPPJQ Here is my Magnum Opus for the week! VEND is a totally 3D Printed candy dispenser that accepts quarters and rejects other coins. VIDEO: http://youtu.be/IWuvwcfnGFE Not only that, it has been designed so that once the loops in the back are secured with a padlock or whatever, it can't come apart (without damage). The back hatch secures the money and access to the coin mechanism's locking pins. The collar around the jar keeps the jar from being removed. The hole on the top will take a preserving lid ring for a standard "medium" Mason jar. That lets you thread the jar to the top, and the collar will secure it in place. Or you can go totally legit and print the provided jar file. (not .JAR file). Also, this version is EXTREMELY generous. For a quarter, it will give you about a dollar's worth of M&Ms, Skittles, Mike and/or Ikes, Chiclets or glass marbles. I don't recommend the marbles. I'll provide a few different drums to adjust the generosity of the machine soon. UPDATE: I've uploaded all the STL files. My prototype is still printing so I'll hold off on the source files until a legitimate test. Stay tuned! If you like what I do and want to help me do more, please consider supporting me on my Patreon page! http://www.patreon.com/ErikJDurwoodII Thanks!
I'll have complete instructions after my prototype is done printing.  Thanks!

title: Printrbot Simple Metal filament tube feed system

description.text:
These are some parts i designed to hold 1/4" clear tubing I used to guide my filament. (see photos).
For printing and assembly instructions see the instructions tab

1) print one (1) "feeder" and two (2) "Filament tube holder"
2) remove extruder tension screw and spring
3) slide "feeder over the extruder arm until you can see the extrusion gears through the hole in the top. ( some minor sanding or cutting may be required to get a perfect fit, but note the hole does not need to be centered, there just needs to be enough room to fit filament through)
4) slide the "filament tube holder"'s over the tops of the Z bars.
5) string your 1/4" tubing through the holes in the tube holders and into the feeder.
6) push filament from the end of the tube until it emerges at the extruder.
7) Happy printing!

title: Universal filament spool cradle with endcaps

description.text:
This is my universal version of Pwnas' adjustable spool holder. I
can drop any of my spools onto it without the need for adjustment.
.
The mosaic feet are his original design based on the work of
bwevans. I found that my threaded rods had rough ends where I
cut them and created the endcaps to cover them and prevent
them from scratching people and nearby things.
.
I used mike_linus' "NUT JOB | Nut, Bolt, Washer and Threaded
Rod Factory" as a starting point and completed the endcap using
sketchup.
.
The real change to the design is that the originals from pwnas and
bwevans were adjustable to fit individual spool widths. I made
mine wider and added additional bearings to accommodate any
of my filament spools without adjustment .
.
This works great on my setup and my "Printrbot Simple Filiment
Guide and Z Axis Stabilizer with Bearings"
( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:444591 ) but it will also work
with any round filament spool feeding any printer

Print 4 of the mosaic feet and four of the endcaps. I printed the
feet with .3 layer height and 15% infill, no support. The endcaps
were also .3 layers and no support, but 100% infill.
.
You need a length of 5/16" threaded rod, twelve 5/16" nuts,
sixteen 5/16" washers, and 608ZZ mini ball bearings from the
hardware store. I got 30 bearings on Amazon for about $18 and
free shipping through prime. I have plenty of them left over for
future projects...
.
The length of the rod and the number of bearings depends on
the width of your spools as described below:
  • The two rods that run front to back are good at 6" (each)
  • The rods that run left to right should be the width of your widest
    spool (in inches) + 2 inches (each)
  • The number of Bearings needed is calculated as:
    (width of widest spool less width of thinnest spool) x 16
    For example, my widest spool is 4", my thinnest spool is 3", so
    the difference is 1 inch, and I need 16 bearings. Round up to
    the next multiple of 4 if you end up with a number not divisible
    by 4.
    .
    Assembly:
  • The two 6" rods are connected with nuts, washers, and an
    endcap through the upper hole of each foot
  • the lower hole in each foot holds threaded rods with the bearings
    on them
  • 1/4 of the bearings go next to each foot as follows:
  • For each side of the rods connected through the lower holes
    (from center to outside, you need a nut, washer, 1/4 of the
    bearings, washer, foot, washer, and endcap)
  • tighten the endcaps and then the internal nuts
    When done, make sure the cradle is square. If not square, your
    spools will "walk" on the cradle to rub on one side during use.
    Your widest spool should fit loosely between the feet. lossen the
    endcaps and separate the feet if necessary
    Your thinnest spool should rest on bearings no matter where you sit
    it between the feet. If it slips off the bearings in the center, add
    more bearings until this can't happen.
    That's it, now you can sit any of your spool on this cradle without
    further adjustments

title: Printrbot Simple 1405 Y-Axis GT2 Belt Tensioner Revised Design Part

description.text:
This is a thicker revised Y-Axis Tensioner.
It actually angles and tips the belt slightly to try and keep it from away from the printer body. It has a 2 degree tilt away from the printer body and the belt loop is tilted 5 degrees to try and keep the belt away from the printer.
M3 Nut cutouts were added for ease of use.

This part is difficult to guide the belt through.
It has an actual full back that gives it more strength.
Clean out the belt loop bar with a paperclip to try and remove any excess printer plastic.
Then cut a thin strip of painter's tape and place it on your belt to extend the belt with a taped end guide.
Work the tape guide through the belt loop carefully and try to grasp and pull out with tweezers, the taped belt portion should follow.
I printed this at around 0.1mm layer height. The screws should fit tight.
I have not extensively tested this part, but the OpenSCAD file is available and you can change the part depth if it is not strong enough.

title: Samsung Galaxy Nexus Collapsible Phone Holder

description.text:
This is a collapsible phone holder for a Samsung Galaxy Nexus. It's base is intended to fit into the credit card holder located inside the dash compartment of my 2006 Scion xB. The whole unit can fold away into the compartment when not in use.   
If you aren't lucky enough to have a Scion...  it could very easily be VHB taped or velcro'd to any flat surface in your auto. If all else fails, it makes for a sturdy, adjustable stand.

Animated Images: Inside the Scion: https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-guuk2UCPUbA/UQh_Jw8nF4I/AAAAAAAABSw/2y7nnvMFMl0/s750/in_car.gif Desktop: https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-j1XWr_dNI28/UQh_Kdk-5vI/AAAAAAAABS4/e4t_y3Xw4fU/s750/on_table.gif Assembly Notes: There are 5 parts in the print. You will need to supply one 1/2"-5/8" long 4-40 screw & nut in order to assemble. Thread the thumbscrew with the screw before assembly. The hole is a bit small and this process will likely require a screwdriver and a pair of pliers to get a good grip while threading. It is also likely you will have to sand and/or shave some material off of the pin that connects the base to the lower clamp section. Do this slowly, it should be a tight fit. This tight fit ensures the stand will hold its position when on an angle.

This case was designed to house the Commodore SD2IEC SD card adapter that is sold online by NKC Electronics. This case will allow you to mount both the mainboard and the daughter boards to keep them protected and looking stylish too!

The case features openings in the front for SD card access, and (2) LED's for Power and Activity lights. You will need (2) standard 5mm LED's. On the back side, you have openings for all the ports, as well as a quick reference guide on setting the drive ID number via the dip switches.   
The mainboard is held in by (2) 3/8" screws in the front, and then the stand offs go between the mainboard and daughter boards, and you will use (2) 1" screws here. The four corners will need to be drilled out to allow the screw to pass through. Sorry, this is the only way I could make them recessed. You need (4) 3/4" screws for the corners.  
I have included the Autodesk 123 files in case someone wants to make any changes. Or, contact me with your suggestions and I'll see what I can do. Enjoy!

Thanks go to conanh for his super cool, "pea-less" 2-tone design!!  
I made a couple of his originals (and they are great!) but I noticed that they didn't seem to have two distinctly different tones.  I watched a few youtubes of whistle builders who made their whistles out of wood, and they demonstrated that, by increasing the size of the output hole, the tone is changed.  (To be fair, they also increased the volume of the chamber- it appears there are a lot of variables!)  
I changed conanh's design by making both chambers the same size, then making chamber 1's output hole smaller, and moving the wedge forward to fit the new smaller hole.  The finished product doesn't have a huge difference between tones, but it is different, and when you hear both together, it is a nice, distinctive sound.  
Oh- and this thing is LOUD!

I printed this with .2mm layer height, 50% infill, 2 vertical shells, 3top/3bottom horizontal shells, and it works great!  
When I tried printing one with layer height of .3, it didn't work as well (my guess is print quality has to be higher for an air-tight whistle)

These are intended for my drop pod, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:446893. To make a full set (you don't have to), you'll need 5 pairs. The STL files include pairs, which need glued together back-to-back. The little notch fits over the control column and the other end fits the inside of the fin. The bottom barely touches the curved part of the fin too.
Printing:

I printed them on high (1mm) in sets of 12 (6 pairs) in ABS. The eagle symbol is almost visible at that resolution.
Variations:
Umbilical:

There are two versions with 1 or 2 "umbilical" slots. The idea is that you can plug a spare bit of filament into the hole and then glue that to the fin. Maybe only do that for 1 or 2 harnesses per pod. You could also just print them all that way and leave the holes empty as an extra greeble.
Singles:

If you want to take out some harnesses, like maybe to see the control pillar more easily, I included some supports for the back that don't have the harness part. There are two variations as I couldn't make up my mind.
General

I've repaired the STL files and they seem to print OK, but there's something wrong with the SketchUp file, sorry. It doesn't seem to like really small stuff, so it was hard to edit. I started making it 10x bigger and then .1x smaller before saving. I probably should've just left it huge and told folks to scale when printing or something.
